00:47:49,950 --> 00:47:53,035
That's good
'cause they're driving, right? OK...

523
00:47:53,120 --> 00:47:55,496
Tell me the story
about why you're sad.

524
00:47:58,166 --> 00:48:00,334
You think l'm sad?

525
00:48:03,088 --> 00:48:05,256
What makes you think that?

526
00:48:07,134 --> 00:48:09,302
Your eyes told me.

527
00:48:11,054 --> 00:48:13,890
l'm not supposed to talk
about stuff like that.

528
00:48:19,897 --> 00:48:21,898
[exhales]

529
00:48:24,985 --> 00:48:28,404
Once upon a time, there was
this person named Malcolm.

530
00:48:28,488 --> 00:48:32,158
He worked with children.

531
00:48:32,242 --> 00:48:34,827
He loved it.

532
00:48:34,912 --> 00:48:37,580
He loved it more than anything else.

533
00:48:40,334 --> 00:48:43,669
And then one night,
he found out that he made a...

534
00:48:43,712 --> 00:48:45,880
...mistake with one of them.

535
00:48:45,964 --> 00:48:48,299
He couldn't help that one.

536
00:48:49,843 --> 00:48:54,513
And he can't stop thinking
about it. He... can't forget.

537
00:48:57,976 --> 00:49:00,645
Ever since then,
things have been different.

538
00:49:02,064 --> 00:49:05,107
He's not the same person
that he used to be.

539
00:49:07,110 --> 00:49:11,864
And his wife... doesn't like
the person that he's become.

540
00:49:11,907 --> 00:49:15,910
They barely speak anymore.
They're like strangers.

541
00:49:19,039 --> 00:49:22,667
And then one day, Malcolm
meets this wonderful little boy.

542
00:49:22,709 --> 00:49:25,544
A really cool little boy.

543
00:49:26,880 --> 00:49:29,382
Reminds him a lot of the other one.

544
00:49:31,718 --> 00:49:34,971
And Malcolm decides
to try and help this new boy...

545
00:49:37,057 --> 00:49:41,769
...'cause he feels that
if he can help this new boy,

546
00:49:41,853 --> 00:49:46,190
be like... helping that other one too.

547
00:49:49,152 --> 00:49:51,904
How does the story end?

548
00:49:53,448 --> 00:49:55,449
l don't know.

549
00:50:12,843 --> 00:50:16,012
l want to tell you my secret now.

550
00:50:20,100 --> 00:50:21,767
OK.

551
00:50:29,484 --> 00:50:32,319
l see dead people.

552
00:50:34,906 --> 00:50:36,907
ln your dreams?

553
00:50:39,036 --> 00:50:41,120
While you're awake?

554
00:50:46,835 --> 00:50:50,504
Dead people, like,
in graves and coffins?

555
00:50:50,589 --> 00:50:53,799
Walking around like regular people.

556
00:50:53,884 --> 00:50:56,886
They don't see each other.

557
00:50:56,970 --> 00:51:00,306
They only see what they want to see.

558
00:51:01,266 --> 00:51:03,601
They don't know they're dead.

559
00:51:05,729 --> 00:51:08,397
How often do you see them?

560
00:51:11,485 --> 00:51:14,320
All the time.

561
00:51:16,364 --> 00:51:18,866
They're everywhere.

562
00:51:21,328 --> 00:51:24,455
You won't tell anyone my secret, right?

563
00:51:24,498 --> 00:51:27,249
No. l promise.

564
00:51:29,086 --> 00:51:32,213
Will you stay here until l fall asleep?

565
00:51:34,007 --> 00:51:35,841
Of course.

566
00:51:44,476 --> 00:51:46,519
[click]

567
00:51:46,603 --> 00:51:51,398
[Malcolm] Cole... has pathologies
more severe than initially assessed.

568
00:51:53,276 --> 00:51:56,153
He's suffering
from visual hallucinations,

569
00:51:56,196 --> 00:51:58,906
- paranoia...
- [tires screeching]

570
00:51:58,990 --> 00:52:03,327
...some kind of...
school-age schizophrenia.

571
00:52:05,163 --> 00:52:08,833
Medication, hospitalization
may be required.

572
00:52:14,131 --> 00:52:16,966
[sighs] And l'm not helping him.

573
00:53:25,785 --> 00:53:27,661
[sighs]

574
00:53:39,132 --> 00:53:41,133
[clears throat]

575
00:53:44,638 --> 00:53:47,139
Hi. This is Lynn Sear, Cole's mom.

576
00:53:48,767 --> 00:53:52,978
Yeah. Uh, yeah, l-l'd like
to talk to you about your boy

577
00:53:53,021 --> 00:53:56,357
and his friends keeping
their goddamn hands off my son.

578
00:55:18,898 --> 00:55:21,233
[shuffling]

579
00:55:33,997 --> 00:55:35,831
Mama?

580
00:55:36,666 --> 00:55:38,167
No.

581
00:55:38,251 --> 00:55:40,336
Dinner is not ready!

582
00:55:40,420 --> 00:55:42,087
What are you gonna do?

583
00:55:42,130 --> 00:55:44,506
Y-You can't hurt me anymore!

584
00:55:46,718 --> 00:55:49,720
Lenny, you're
a terrible husband, Lenny!

585
00:55:49,763 --> 00:55:53,057
Look what you made me do! Lenny!

586
00:55:53,099 --> 00:55:55,434
[Cole sobbing]

587
00:56:03,485 --> 00:56:06,945
[panting] l'm OK. OK. OK.

588
00:56:12,327 --> 00:56:14,578
[Tommy] Once there was a boy,

589
00:56:14,621 --> 00:56:17,414
very different from all the other boys.

590
00:56:17,457 --> 00:56:20,125
He lived in the jungle...

591
00:56:21,294 --> 00:56:24,088
...and he could speak
to the animals.

592
00:56:24,130 --> 00:56:27,466
- [piano music]
- [camcorders whirring]

593
00:56:28,510 --> 00:56:31,637
[kids making animal noises]

594
00:56:31,679 --> 00:56:33,847
[applause]

595
00:56:38,937 --> 00:56:41,688
[Cole] Did you think
the play sucked big time?

596
00:56:41,773 --> 00:56:44,650
Heh. What?

597
00:56:44,734 --> 00:56:47,736
Tommy Tammisimo acted
in a cough syrup commercial.

598
00:56:47,821 --> 00:56:51,073
He said everyone was
self-conscious and unrealistic.

599
00:56:51,157 --> 00:56:53,409
He said the play sucked big time.

600
00:56:53,493 --> 00:56:56,245
This Tommy kid sounds like a real punk.

601
00:56:57,914 --> 00:57:01,917
l thought the play was
excellent. Better than Cats.

602
00:57:02,001 --> 00:57:04,503
- Cats?
- Never mind.

603
00:57:06,339 --> 00:57:08,257
Cole, l was really interested

604
00:57:08,341 --> 00:57:10,467
in what you told me at the hospital.

605
00:57:10,510 --> 00:57:13,011
l'd like to hear more about it.

606
00:57:23,106 --> 00:57:24,940
Cole?

607
00:57:27,861 --> 00:57:29,528
What?

608
00:57:42,709 --> 00:57:44,710
Something up there?

609
00:57:49,507 --> 00:57:51,341
Cole?

610
00:57:54,888 --> 00:57:56,889
l don't see anything.

611
00:58:01,269 --> 00:58:03,270
Be real still.

612
00:58:07,901 --> 00:58:10,235
Sometimes you feel it inside,

613
00:58:10,320 --> 00:58:13,030
like you're falling down real fast,

614
00:58:13,072 --> 00:58:15,741
but you're really just standing still.

615
00:58:20,663 --> 00:58:25,083
Do you ever feel the prickly
things on the back of your neck?

616
00:58:25,126 --> 00:58:27,794
Yes.

617
00:58:27,879 --> 00:58:31,965
And the tiny hairs on your arm,
you know, when they stand up?

618
00:58:32,050 --> 00:58:33,884
Yes.

619
00:58:36,221 --> 00:58:38,222
That's them.

620
00:58:41,518 --> 00:58:43,685
When they get mad...

621
00:58:47,774 --> 00:58:49,775
...it gets cold.

622
00:59:06,918 --> 00:59:10,921
l don't see anything.
Are you sure they're there?

623
00:59:12,590 --> 00:59:14,424
Cole?

624
00:59:16,553 --> 00:59:19,429
Please make them leave.

625
00:59:19,472 --> 00:59:21,473
l'm workin' on it.

626
00:59:23,851 --> 00:59:25,686
Come on.

627
00:59:53,214 --> 00:59:56,216
Aah! [laughing]

628
01:00:11,024 --> 01:00:13,358
Mommy, Daddy?

629
01:00:14,485 --> 01:00:16,361
[coughing]

630
01:00:16,404 --> 01:00:18,739
My throat hurts.

631
01:00:27,290 --> 01:00:29,124
Run! Run!

632
01:00:30,710 --> 01:00:33,003
[announcer]
Pedia Ease cough suppressant.

633
01:00:33,046 --> 01:00:35,422
Gentle, fast, eff...

634
01:00:35,506 --> 01:00:37,758
Cole.

635
01:00:37,842 --> 01:00:41,553
Oh, l don't care what they say.
This thing is broken.

636
01:00:49,395 --> 01:00:51,396
Take 'em off.

637
01:00:55,318 --> 01:00:57,486
l don't want them on my table.

638
01:01:02,200 --> 01:01:05,369
l saw what was in your bureau
drawer when l was cleaning.

639
01:01:05,411 --> 01:01:07,621
Got something you want to confess?

640
01:01:10,583 --> 01:01:12,167
Hmm?

641
01:01:12,251 --> 01:01:15,921
The bumblebee pendant?
Why do you keep taking it?

642
01:01:20,551 --> 01:01:22,719
lt was Grandma's.

643
01:01:22,762 --> 01:01:26,098
You know, what if it broke?
You know how sad l'd be.

644
01:01:28,267 --> 01:01:31,269
You'd cry 'cause you
miss Grandma so much.

645
01:01:32,271 --> 01:01:34,272
That's right.

646
01:01:38,528 --> 01:01:42,197
Sometimes people think
they lose things...

647
01:01:43,991 --> 01:01:47,828
...and they really didn't
lose them, it just gets moved.

648
01:01:47,912 --> 01:01:50,414
So did you move
the bumblebee pendant?

649
01:01:58,297 --> 01:02:00,215
Don't get mad.

650
01:02:00,299 --> 01:02:02,342
So who moved it this time?

651
01:02:02,427 --> 01:02:05,762
Maybe someone came in our house,
took the bumblebee pendant

652
01:02:05,805 --> 01:02:08,890
out of my closet and placed
it nicely in your drawer.

653
01:02:10,143 --> 01:02:13,562
- Maybe.
- God, l am so tired, Cole.

654
01:02:13,646 --> 01:02:16,148
l'm tired in my body,
l'm tired in my mind,

655
01:02:16,190 --> 01:02:18,984
l'm... tired in my heart.

656
01:02:19,068 --> 01:02:22,320
l need some help. You know,
l don't know if you noticed,

657
01:02:22,405 --> 01:02:25,699
but our little family
isn't doing so good.

658
01:02:25,783 --> 01:02:30,162
l mean, l've been praying,
but l must not be praying right.

659
01:02:30,204 --> 01:02:34,666
Looks like we're just gonna have
to answer each other's prayers.

660
01:02:37,545 --> 01:02:40,714
lf we can't talk to each other,
we're not gonna make it.

661
01:02:44,051 --> 01:02:47,721
Now, tell me, baby.
l-l... l won't get mad, honey.

662
01:02:47,805 --> 01:02:50,640
Did you take the bumblebee pendant?

663
01:02:58,858 --> 01:03:01,359
- No.
- [silverware clatters]

664
01:03:03,070 --> 01:03:06,406
You've had enough roast beef.
You need to leave the table.

665
01:03:08,451 --> 01:03:10,118
Go!

666
01:03:20,671 --> 01:03:23,173
[barking, whimpering]

667
01:03:27,386 --> 01:03:29,221
[gasps]

668
01:03:33,309 --> 01:03:35,227
Hey, come on.

669
01:03:35,311 --> 01:03:38,146
l'll show you where
my dad keeps his gun. Come on.

670
01:03:40,817 --> 01:03:42,651
[dog whimpering]

671
01:03:43,945 --> 01:03:47,364
[sobbing] Sebastian, come on.

672
01:03:47,406 --> 01:03:49,241
Mama?

673
01:03:55,915 --> 01:03:58,583
lf you're not very mad,

674
01:03:58,668 --> 01:04:01,336
can l sleep in your bed tonight?

675
01:04:03,172 --> 01:04:05,674
Look at my face.

676
01:04:05,758 --> 01:04:07,926
l'm not very mad.

677
01:04:13,057 --> 01:04:15,559
Baby, why are you shaking?

678
01:04:16,644 --> 01:04:18,812
Cole, what's wrong?

679
01:04:18,896 --> 01:04:22,691
Oh, God, please tell me!

680
01:04:22,775 --> 01:04:24,776
Oh, please.

681
01:04:28,322 --> 01:04:30,156
Oh.

682
01:04:38,958 --> 01:04:40,959
[Anna] lt's Edwardian,

683
01:04:41,002 --> 01:04:43,795
beautifully worked
with mine-cut diamonds

684
01:04:43,880 --> 01:04:47,132
and an actual color Burmese sapphire.

685
01:04:47,216 --> 01:04:49,843
lt's timeless.

686
01:04:49,927 --> 01:04:51,761
Oh.

687
01:04:52,722 --> 01:04:54,973
You, uh... [clears throat]

688
01:04:55,057 --> 01:04:57,225
...got anything a little plainer?

689
01:04:57,310 --> 01:04:59,144
Plainer?

690
01:04:59,186 --> 01:05:02,814
You want a plain ring to go with
your plain fianc‚? ls that how it is?

691
01:05:02,899 --> 01:05:06,067
No! Baby, don't... don't get in a tizzy.

692
01:05:08,905 --> 01:05:10,655
Uh...

693
01:05:10,740 --> 01:05:13,450
You're so beautiful.

694
01:05:13,492 --> 01:05:17,162
Y-You're like a Burmese
sapphire all by yourself.

695
01:05:17,246 --> 01:05:20,206
- You don't need all that.
- Uh-huh.

696
01:05:20,291 --> 01:05:24,961
Why don't you try it on and see
how you both feel about it?

697
01:05:30,343 --> 01:05:32,677
There. How does that feel?

698
01:05:34,013 --> 01:05:37,641
l think this piece, um,
communicates a longing.

699
01:05:37,683 --> 01:05:41,311
l imagine that the woman who owned it

700
01:05:41,354 --> 01:05:44,189
loved a man that she couldn't be with.

701
01:05:45,942 --> 01:05:49,152
Did he have wavy hair and chestnut eyes?

702
01:05:49,195 --> 01:05:53,323
- What?
- Um, l-l don't know, but...

703
01:05:53,366 --> 01:05:56,326
...a lot of the pieces
in this store communicate,

704
01:05:56,369 --> 01:05:59,704
and l think you should choose
a piece that speaks to you.

705
01:06:01,332 --> 01:06:05,418
l think maybe when people own
things and then they pass away,

706
01:06:05,503 --> 01:06:09,631
a part of themselves gets
printed on those things,

707
01:06:09,715 --> 01:06:13,218
like... like fingerprints.

708
01:06:14,762 --> 01:06:16,930
l'll just wrap it up.

709
01:06:24,355 --> 01:06:26,606
You don't need a guy with a master's.

710
01:06:26,691 --> 01:06:29,776
You need a wrestler with
a neck larger than his head.

711
01:06:29,860 --> 01:06:32,779
[chuckles] No, l need
a wrestler with a master's.

712
01:06:34,115 --> 01:06:36,574
- What's this?
- Happy birthday.

713
01:06:36,617 --> 01:06:38,618
- From you?
- Mm-hmm.

714
01:06:46,419 --> 01:06:48,420
lt's a...

715
01:06:48,504 --> 01:06:50,588
...first edition.

716
01:06:50,673 --> 01:06:52,590
- Wow.
- [giggles]

717
01:06:52,675 --> 01:06:54,843
Oh, this is too much.

718
01:06:54,927 --> 01:06:58,430
No. Took it out
of your Christmas bonus.

719
01:06:59,849 --> 01:07:02,600
lt's perfect, Anna.

720
01:07:02,685 --> 01:07:04,769
Thanks.

721
01:07:04,854 --> 01:07:06,855
[chuckles]

722
01:07:10,609 --> 01:07:13,570
[Cole] What do you want
more than anything?

723
01:07:13,612 --> 01:07:15,613
[Malcolm] l don't know.

724
01:07:15,698 --> 01:07:17,824
[Cole] l told you what l want.

725
01:07:17,908 --> 01:07:20,243
- [bang, glass breaking]
- [gasps]

726
01:07:21,454 --> 01:07:23,621
[Malcolm] l know what l want.

727
01:07:25,499 --> 01:07:28,334
l want to be able
to talk to my wife again...

728
01:07:30,129 --> 01:07:32,630
...the way we used
to talk to each other...

729
01:07:34,175 --> 01:07:36,926
...like there was no one
else in the world except us.

730
01:07:38,804 --> 01:07:40,972
[Cole] How are you gonna do that?

731
01:07:44,143 --> 01:07:46,102
[sighs]

732
01:07:46,145 --> 01:07:48,480
l can't be
your doctor anymore.

733
01:07:48,522 --> 01:07:52,567
l haven't paid enough
attention to my family.

734
01:07:52,651 --> 01:07:55,320
Bad things happen
when you do that.

735
01:07:56,822 --> 01:07:59,449
Do you understand?

736
01:07:59,492 --> 01:08:02,077
l'm going to transfer you.
l know two psychol...

737
01:08:02,161 --> 01:08:04,496
Don't fail me.

738
01:08:05,998 --> 01:08:09,918
Don't give up. You're the only
one who can help me. l know it.

739
01:08:10,002 --> 01:08:12,170
l can't help you.

740
01:08:14,840 --> 01:08:17,175
You...

741
01:08:17,259 --> 01:08:19,594
Someone else can help you.

742
01:08:22,515 --> 01:08:24,849
You believe me, right?

743
01:08:29,355 --> 01:08:32,190
Dr. Crowe, you believe my secret, right?

744
01:08:34,068 --> 01:08:37,112
l don't know how
to answer that, Cole.

745
01:08:47,123 --> 01:08:50,041
How can you help me...

746
01:08:50,084 --> 01:08:52,752
...if you don't believe me?

747
01:08:56,715 --> 01:08:59,717
Some magic's real.

748
01:09:15,860 --> 01:09:19,195
[Vincent] Do you know why
you're afraid when you're alone?

749
01:09:21,198 --> 01:09:24,159
l do. l do.

750
01:09:28,080 --> 01:09:29,789
[click, tape hissing]

751
01:09:29,874 --> 01:09:32,250
[Malcolm] l'm sorry about that, Vincent.

752
01:09:32,334 --> 01:09:35,044
l hope l didn't leave
you alone too long.

